text: Nice liberal propaganda, hollywood. I knew just from the title alone that this would be peddling the typical global warming (oh wait, now it's "climate change") bullshit that tries to make sense of our chaotic, unpredictable weather systems (about as feasible as random number interpolation) and subsequently changes drastically every decade or so. Those "climate scientists" over at NASA are really wasting their decent brainpower-- maybe they should, perhaps, direct their attention towards aeronautics and space...  The fact that this trailer additionally references self-driving cars, which are a phantom technology that silicon valley is shilling in order to push the concept of a universal basic income, which if passed would ultimately prevent the passage of legislation limiting workforce automation and allow for a reentry into serfdom, allows me to begin my argument. Self-driving cars are the easiest way for silicon valley to demonstrate the cataclysmic consequences of widespread automation without effective legislation in place. What they don't want you to know, however, is that universal basic income is not a real solution to the problems created by this push towards a fully automated workforce that they are responsible for. Even with UBI, society would eventually converge to a point at which the entire means of production would be owned by a single conglomerate that would be free to control the public however they saw fit. UBI is masquerading as some holy grail of a socialist society wherein everyone is freed from "those pesky corporate overlords," but it would actually result in the opposite taking place-- through paying a standard wage to everyone, UBI deincentivizes those who have lost their jobs due to automation from finding a new job, or, most importantly, backing legislation that would prevent further automation of the workforce. Liberals love pushing for UBI to seem progressive and enlightened, while at the same time considering all the CEOs and corporations to be the roots of all evils of our society, yet they fail to see the fact that the prior plays directly into the hand of the latter.  The US Govt (the military industrial complex) has effectively prevented its citizens from responding to major issues over the past three decades through false flag over false flag. Its most impressive success as of now was the revelation of widespread surveillance of its citizens being met with virtually no public protest. As the complex continues to tighten its grip on its citizens, you can be sure that their interests will not align with the interests of their citizens. UBI is only one example of a false flag; climate change is yet another.  The military industrial complex wants the public to view science the same way Europeans viewed the Catholic church before the reformation. We are slowly entering a new dark age, where assertions that have been published in papers must be heralded as the word of God. Note, too, that through funding research and publications, the military industrial complex has complete control over what gets published and what is never even given the chance to be tested. The leaders of the military industrial complex will effectively become the silent guiding hands of this new church. The worst part is that refuting this new church through logic will become increasingly difficult as the years go on, and so the walls guarding this new world will climb higher and higher. As this church-in-disguise shapes human knowledge, logic itself will slowly become eroded until refutation of the scientific method is impossible. This is already happening to some extent (See Robert Pirsig).  In conclusion, climate change is bullshit, science itself is becoming bullshit, UBI is bullshit, the US Govt is poisoning our water supply, Christ returned already and was killed by the Grand Inquisitor, and Bush did 9/11 xd

text: Ok...............apart from the stuff that is probably gonna make Neil Degrasse Tyson switch from beer to whiskey.............This is EXACTLY what I talk about when I hear people say "Superman is too powerful".  Dude, just put him in bigger disasters.  Armies of robots from the future. World wide storms created by a mad scientist. Giant monsters from another dimension. Name a movie YOU ONLY REMEMBER for the special effects and put Superman in it.  2012, Sky Captain and the World of Tomorrow, Pacific Rim, The day after Tomorrow, War of the Worlds........I am not saying that these films SHOULD have been Superman films. I am just saying that we forget the "This looks like a job for Superman" part of his mythos. He is a fantastic hero IN A FANTASTIC WORLD! A world where 5th dimensional gods come by to troll mankind by altering the fabric of reality, where an evil robot sun wants to replace our own sun with itself, where a green man from outer space keeps civilizations in jars, where armies of new gods battle for supremacy at the edge of space. Superman never needed a messiah complex. He needed a safe place to put his friends before he ran off to headbut cthulhu before dressing up as flash gordon for a lightsaber eating contest.

text: Spoilers for: Geostorm (2017)  Geostorm is most likely one of the worst movies of 2017, the biggest reason I would have to say is the whole "mystery part".Since it was very simple to figure out who it was. The plot is that there is a space weather station that goes haywire and many people in the movie think its a glitch or malfunction. But no, it was somebody doing it on purpose. So the characters are Leonidas, the nerd from National Treasure, and some other people. So it starts out with some serious not cringey at all exposition by some 9 yr old girl. ANd wow the girl is Leonidas's daughter, their relationship throughout this movie was AWFUL. Here are some reasons why: She acts independent even though she is 9,wait 13 BUT SHE LOOKS NINE BRO She dumps all information into everything she says, she‚Äôs like oh, ur not reliable dad...I mean she knows that but we don‚Äôt know Another trait many of these heroes in movies are at least one of these; Late to important meetings Dead-beat dad Etc Etc Another awful aspect was the visuals and music, i don‚Äôt know much about ‚Äúspecial effects‚Äù and ‚Äúscoring‚Äù or whatever so don‚Äôt expect much. The music felt undeserved when stuff is going on. So let me give an example, Leonidas and National Treasure are brothers so N.T was put in charge of the 300‚Äôs project and he was pissed. So the gov. Guys needed to send him up back to the  space station and they sent N.T to convince his brother to go. So this is all we knew about their relationship at this point in the movie: Their brothers Their parents died N.T hasn‚Äôt been in the daughter life a lot Leonidas doesn‚Äôt listen/respect his brothers actions  So there wasn‚Äôt much build up to their conversation about him going to space, but the music is treating it like we have been through their entire lives through thick and thin but i digress. One other major problem is the special effects, yes the trailers were half good because of the destruction but other than that they gave up. I can‚Äôt describe it so let‚Äôs go to the next point.
author: Nico

text: Spoilers for: Geostorm (2017)  Geostorm is most likely one of the worst movies of 2017, the biggest reason I would have to say is the whole "who did it".Since it was very simple to figure out who it was, but not why they did what they did. The plot is that there is a space weather station (A station in space that can alter weather)that goes haywire and many people in the movie think its a glitch or malfunction. It was somebody doing it on purpose. So the characters are Gerard Butler,Jim Sturgess ,and some other people. So it starts out with some exposition by some 13 year old girl. And wow the girl is Gerard Butler‚Äôs daughter, their relationship throughout this movie was AWFUL. Here are some reasons why: She acts independent even though she is 9,wait 13  She dumps all information into everything she says, she‚Äôs like oh, you are not reliable dad...I mean she knows that but we don‚Äôt know, there could have been a better way to reveal Another trait many of these heroes in movies are at least one of these; Late to important meetings Not the best parent Etc Etc Another awful aspect was the visuals and music, I don‚Äôt know much about ‚Äúspecial effects‚Äù and ‚Äúscoring‚Äù or whatever so don‚Äôt expect much. Also there was a timer, timers in many movies are the worst. They are meant to be scary/suspenseful because ‚ÄúIf the timer runs out _____ and ____ will happen.‚Äù But what it boils down to is the movie making pointless obstacles to get the timer down to one second. The music felt undeserved when something  is going on. So let me give an example,Gerard Butler and Jim Sturgess are brothers so Jim was put in charge of Gerard Butler‚Äôs project and he was pissed.( He was so pissed he han‚Äôt had contact with his brother for 3   years and calling him a stranger when he sees him again.) So the government guys needed to send him up back to the  space station and they sent to convince his brother to go. So this is all we knew about their relationship at this point in the movie: Their brothers Their parents died Gerard Butler doesn‚Äôt listen/respect his brothers actions (Example: During a press conference JIm told Gerard helpful information via texts and Gerard didn‚Äôt care) So there wasn‚Äôt much build up to their conversation about him going to space, but the music is treating it like we have been through their entire lives through thick and thin but i digress. One other major problem is the special effects, yes the trailers were half good because of the destruction but other than that there wasn‚Äôt as much effort. I can‚Äôt describe it so let‚Äôs go to the next point. The acting was fine out of the one person you‚Äôd expect but everyone else,besides a couple actors, were below average, judging acting isn‚Äôt my best place to ‚Äúcritique‚Äù.  Overall this movie wasn‚Äôt that good, on a scale 1-10 this movie would have a 4/10

text: I loved and hated this movie. Good FX. Fantastic idea for plot. Acting was pretty good. Writing not so much. It's worth watching for the FX alone but they really missed the mark by making it a by the numbers planet disaster movie. I think someone mislabeled their "fresh ideas" outline and their "stay away from these cliches" outline. It's worth your time but keep those expectations in check and make full use of that "realism switch" in your head. Movies are not supposed to be 100% when it comes to survival but wow. Surviving space disasters was pushed to a whole new level. Have a watch and have fun. FYI. Everything that happens in space in the last 1/3 of the movie really pushes the limits even with my "yea that could happen" switch turned to 11. Then again most people ignore space junk now but come on!

A mere two years from when the movie was made, the weather grew so horrible that Paris and Manhattan floods, 2 million die in Madrid from a heat wave in a single DAY?!  Sorry, but what climate scenario is THAT bad?!  The idea that we could create satellites that can control the weather in such a scenario is believable.  As one author put it, we have a genius for survival.  The idea that said satellites could and would be turned into a weapon?  Even more believable, after all, what WON'T we turn into a weapon?  The conspiracy is believable, and the one behind it was unexpected, the only hint I had was who played the one behind it.

text: Normally one should avoid any movie with '-storm' in the name for the 95% chance of it being a B-movie, but this was awesome. I didn't check the details, so when Gerald Butler entered the scene I had a smile on my face.The weather events were all little too comical i.e. a tsunami in a desert, but overall really awesome. Next bit is about the ending, so SPOILER:  The ending was a bit cheesy though. Every human being having the look on their face of 'we've been saved'. Normally people would've been terrified. Neither can you tell me that storms that have been conjured up just subside 5 seconds after pressing a button. Actually humanity is still screwed because the 'net' was the only thing keeping earthly phenomena from going nuts. Guess this is the Independence Day-syndrome. These days movies have become more realistic, so I wish they would've done that with the ending too, but guess a typical Hollywood ending will have to suffice. Otherwise really great movie though!
